# ‚úÖ Ubuntu Training Handbook ‚Äì Part 1 (Modules 1‚Äì10)

This handbook covers foundational Ubuntu Linux commands and system operations for beginners.

---

# üî∞ Module 1: Introduction to Ubuntu

Basic system identification commands:

```bash
whoami       # Show current user
hostname     # Show system hostname
uname -a     # Show OS and kernel info
```

---

# üß∞ Module 2: Basic File Commands

## üìÅ Creating & Managing Files/Folders

```bash
mkdir test_folder     # Create new folder
cd test_folder        # Navigate into folder
touch file1.txt       # Create an empty file
ls -l                 # List files with details
ls -a                 # List all files (including hidden files)
rm file1.txt          # Delete a file
cd ..                 # Go up one level
rmdir test_folder     # Remove empty folder
```

---

## üìä File Size & Disk Usage Commands

| Command | Description | Example |
|----------|-------------|----------|
| `ls -lh filename` | Shows file size in human-readable format (KB, MB) | `ls -lh myfile.txt` |
| `du -h filename` | Shows disk usage of a file | `du -h cron_test.log` |
| `du -sh filename` | Shows only total size | `du -sh myfile.txt` |
| `stat filename` | Detailed file info (size in bytes) | `stat myfile.txt` |
| `stat -c%s filename` | Outputs only file size in bytes | `stat -c%s myfile.txt` |
| `du -sh *` | Shows sizes of all files/folders in directory | `du -sh *` |
| `du -sh /path/to/folder` | Shows total size of folder | `du -sh ~/Downloads` |
| `find . -type f -exec du -h {} +` | Lists file sizes recursively | Same |
| `ls -lhS` | Lists files sorted by size (descending) | `ls -lhS` |

### üî• Top 10 Largest Files

```bash
du -a | sort -n -r | head -n 10
```

---

# üìÇ Module 3: File Viewing and Editing

```bash
echo "Ubuntu Training" > sample.txt   # Create file with text
cat sample.txt                        # View file content
nano sample.txt                       # Edit file using nano
```

---

# üì¶ Module 4: Package Management

```bash
sudo apt update                      # Update package list
sudo apt upgrade                     # Upgrade installed packages
sudo apt install cowsay              # Install cowsay
cowsay "Hello, Ubuntu!"              # Run cowsay
cowsay -f moose "hi"                 # Run cowsay with different character
sudo apt remove cowsay               # Uninstall cowsay
```

---

# üë• Module 5: User Management

```bash
sudo adduser testuser               # Create new user
su - testuser                       # Switch to user
exit                                # Exit from user
sudo usermod -aG sudo testuser      # Add user to sudo group
sudo deluser testuser               # Delete user
```

---

# üîê Module 6: File Permissions

```bash
touch file.txt                      # Create a file
ls -l file.txt                      # Show permissions
ls -lh file.txt                     # Human-readable file size
chmod 755 file.txt                  # Change permissions
ls -l file.txt                      # Confirm change
```

Example permission:

```
-rw-rw-r-- 1 testuser testuser 0 Jul 14 19:57 file.txt
```

- `rw-` ‚Üí Owner: read and write  
- `rw-` ‚Üí Group: read and write  
- `r--` ‚Üí Others: read  

## üî¢ Permission Reference Table

| Octal | Symbolic | Meaning |
|--------|----------|---------|
| 7 | rwx | Read, write, execute |
| 6 | rw- | Read, write |
| 5 | r-x | Read, execute |
| 4 | r-- | Read only |
| 0 | --- | No permissions |

Examples:

```bash
chmod 755 file.txt   # rwxr-xr-x
chmod 600 file.txt   # 100% private
```

---

# üåê Module 7: Networking Basics

```bash
ip a                                # Show IP address info
ping -c 4 google.com                # Test internet connection
```

---

# üß™ Module 8: Bash Scripting Introduction

Create the script:

```bash
nano hello.sh
```

Paste into file:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
echo "Welcome to Ubuntu!"
```

Run the script:

```bash
chmod +x hello.sh                  # Make executable
./hello.sh                         # Execute script
```

---

# üóÇÔ∏è Module 9: System Monitoring

```bash
top                                 # Live system monitor
htop                                # Advanced process viewer
free -h                             # Check memory usage
df -h                               # Disk space usage
```

### Process Management Example

```bash
# Create script
echo -e '#!/bin/bash\nwhile true; do echo "Looping..."; sleep 2; done' > loop.sh
chmod +x loop.sh

# Run in background
./loop.sh &

# Find PID
pgrep -f loop.sh

# Kill process
kill PID
```

If htop is not installed:

```bash
sudo apt install htop
```

---

# üîç Module 10: Searching and Finding Files

```bash
sudo updatedb                      # Update locate database
locate bash                        # Search for files containing 'bash'
find /etc -name "*.conf"           # Find .conf files in /etc
grep 'root' /etc/passwd            # Search inside file
```

If locate is not available:

```bash
sudo apt install plocate
```

